TikTok hides from users unwanted videos
According to TikTok, the number of its users in the world exceeds 500 million, 40% of which are under 18 years old.
Imagine China / Reuters
Chinese social network TikTok is censoring videos that mention Tiananmen Square, Tibet’s independence, or the banned Falun Gong religious group, The Guardian reports.
The documents, which appeared in the publication, say that the owner of TikTok (the company ByteDance) with the help of the application promotes the goals of China's foreign policy abroad.
Most of the violations related to China’s policies fall under “incitement of hatred”.
In each case, TikTok places unsolicited posts in a context appropriate to the general rules, so that the actions of the social network do not look censored.
For example, the ban on criticism of China’s socialist system falls under the general ban on “criticism or attacks on the policies and social rules of any country, such as constitutional monarchy, parliamentary system, etc.”
The ban on mentioning Tiananmen Square incidents or the genocide in Cambodia falls under the “distortion of the history of China or other countries.”
The document also lists the banned names of 20 "foreign leaders or statesmen" including North Korean leaders Kim Jong Il, Kim Il Sung and Kim Jong-un, Indian politician Mahatma Gandhi, U.S. President Donald Trump and Barack Obama, Japanese Prime Minister Shinzo Abe, and South Korean presidents.
Prohibited material is divided into two categories, the document says.
Posts from the first category are deleted by the administrators of the social network and may lead to the blocking of the user.
Not too severe violations belong to the second category: such publications remain on the site, but their distribution is limited to TikTok algorithms.
ByteDance told The Guardian that these rules are outdated and no longer applicable: “We are now using a localized approach for moderation, as well as engaging independent local professionals.”
Russian users of TikTok have no specific restrictions on publication, says Rustem Bogdanov, co-founder of the Production Center.
"Production Center" is one of the Russian media companies that officially cooperates with TikTok.
All promotional materials of bloggers "Production Center" agrees with representatives of the social network, but user materials can be posted without consent, Bogdanov reports.
Asked if TikTok could speak about politics or Putin, Bogdanov answered affirmatively and said he had seen such publications.
With Bogdanov agrees the founder of the agency Our Didgital Roman Zaripov: "The basic rules for users TikTok lists in the user agreement: it is impossible to post shocking content, discriminatory statements and so on."
But under these rules, you can bring any content that the moderators do not like, says Zaripov.
Zaripova Agency is another Russian partner of TikTok.
According to TikTok, the number of its users in the world exceeds 500 million, 40% of which are under 18 years old.
Under the user agreement, TikTok can only be used by persons over 13 years of age.
Social network administrators check their age with artificial intelligence: the neural network analyzes faces and determines how old a person looks, Bogdanov says.
If the neural network decides that the user is younger, his account can be deleted, he adds.
According to RBC, in September 2019 ByteDance opened an office in Moscow on the territory of WeWork coworking.
