This is reported by TASS with reference to the press service of the European Southern Observatory (ESO).
According to ESO, this week officially began the construction of the dome of the building, which will house the European Extremely Large Telescope (E-ELT) while the most expensive and ambitious ground-based astronomical project.
Its total cost is estimated by ESO to exceed one billion euros.
Most of this money will be spent on the manufacture of equipment and construction of the building of the observatory.
The most expensive and complex component of the telescope is its record-breaking large mirror, whose diameter will be about 39 meters.
It will be assembled from 798 hexagonal segments measuring 1.4 meters.
This huge mirror, as well as two auxiliary reflecting surfaces with a diameter of 4.2 and 3.75 meters, will help E-ELT get the first detailed pictures of planets outside the solar system, stars in other galaxies, and also look for Earth's twins.
In addition, scientists will try to use this observatory to observe the vicinity of Sgr A*, a supermassive black hole at the center of the Milky Way.
Despite the fact that the construction of the dome has just begun, mirrors, scientific instruments and other components of the observatory scientists, engineers and other specialists have been developing for three years - since the announcement of the first plans for the construction of the E-ELT.
The contract for the production of the main mirror, whose total cost was about 400 million euros, was awarded to the German company SCHOTT and the French company Safran Reosc.
